Moduli 

One interesting feature of this ansatz is that the
parameter , describing
the volume of , does not appear in the equations
of motion even in the
case of a curved internal space. Moreover, the positions of
both branes are free at
the classical level.  They correspond to flat directions in
the action and thus
are the relevant degrees of freedom at low energies. In the
moduli
approximation, which we shall follow here, they are promoted
to four dimensional
scalar fields.

One crucial difference of these solutions with respect to the RS
model is that they are not homogeneous along the orbifold, even in
the case when  is a torus (In this case, the
solution corresponds to a toroidal compactification of a higher
dimensional  space.) . This is due to the compactness of
. In contrast with the RS model, the positions of both
branes are physically meaningful.

However, it is clear that a scaling of  is equivalent to
a shift in the
positions of the branes . Therefore, they are not
independent. Rather,
only two moduli are needed. Since we will use several
