Let us now examine the constraints that we have on the moduli and
the physical values they can take.  First of all, we are thinking
of an inter-brane distance  somewhat larger than the
inverse curvature scale  of the bulk, in order to have a
substantial redshift factor .  On the other hand, the
smallest physical length scale is given by the size of  at
the negative tension brane, . This cannot be smaller than the
fundamental length of the theory  though, as argued in the
previous paragraph, it should be close to it. There is a tighter
technical restriction which we shall use so that the result for
the potential () is valid. This, is organized as a
power series in , and can be trusted only when
 a bit larger than the curvature scale and  a factor
 above (recall that the ratio  coincides with the
redshift factor ).
Incidentally, we remark that this corresponds to the physical situation where
the size of the internal manifold  is everywhere  smaller than the
inter-brane distance .  (This means that in a certain range
  of energy the model is effectively 5 dimensional.



