It remains to be seen that, indeed, the graviton KK modes along the orbifold are
unobservable, in spite of their relatively small masses .
We see from Eqs.  (,) that the (unnormalized) wave function
of the KK modes grows exponentially as , signaling that the more
warped the extra dimensions are, the more localized on the negative tension
brane these modes are.  This implies that the coupling of these
graviton KK modes is amplified with respect to that of the zero mode (
) by a factor . Then, they are much more weakly
coupled to matter  than in the RS model ().
Thus, in spite of their relatively small mass, these KK gravitons cannot be seen
individually in accelerators. 
Moreover, since they are associated with only one off-the-brane dimension,
they do not have as large a multiplicity as in the usual large volume mechanism
, and so they do not significantly cool stars.  The total rate of
emission of any of such gravitons at a given energy  can be estimated as
the coupling squared times the number of states with masses lighter than 
,





which is very small for the  energies available  inside stars.











































